<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="70" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,638,1443,1729]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,290,1655,1676]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named for LSAM alumnus, lab mate, and enthusiastic supporter of this study, Matthew L. Gimmel.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="70" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="69.[685,1173,194,1065]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,814,194,215]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species can be distinguished from the other species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Broun" authorityYear="1911" box="[999,1080,221,242]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Sagola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auripila">
<emphasis box="[999,1080,221,242]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">auripila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
speciesgroup by the following combination of characters: larger body, length 
<quantity box="[933,1013,274,295]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
; antennomere 1 approximately 2 times longer than wide, with dull surface; gular region of male head depressed and densely setose; frontal sulcus deep, reaching vertexal fovea; shape of genitalia unique to species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="70" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="69.[685,1173,194,1065]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,920,433,454]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Description of Male.</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity box="[1018,1103,433,454]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
. Body brown, antennae, legs, maxillary palpi, and elytra paler (
<figureCitation box="[754,848,486,507]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[197,229,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[193,1176,940,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-360@64.[173,1193,920,1671]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 37. Habitus of Sagola species in the auripila species-group, dorsal views. a) S. auripila, b) S. spiniventris," figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907837/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[807,848,486,507]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="3.7" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="g" value="37.0">37g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[872,936,486,507]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Head:</emphasis>
Round, widest across eyes (
<figureCitation box="[751,848,513,534]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[197,229,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[193,1176,940,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-360@64.[173,1193,920,1671]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 37. Habitus of Sagola species in the auripila species-group, dorsal views. a) S. auripila, b) S. spiniventris," figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907837/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[806,848,513,534]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="3.7" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="g" value="37.0">37g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
). Gular region depressed and densely setose. Antennomere 1 approximately 2 times longer than wide, with dull surface, 2–3 subquadrate, 4–5 longer than wide, 6–10 subquadrate. Frontal sulcus deep, reaching end of head from frontal rostrum. Anterior frontal fovea round and partially covered by frontal rostrum, posterior frontal fovea elongate. Eye small, approximately one-third length of temple. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1088,1171,725,746]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Thorax:</emphasis>
Prosternum as long as wide, widest at midpoint. Elytra approximately triangular (
<figureCitation box="[1006,1092,778,799]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[197,229,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[193,1176,940,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-360@64.[173,1193,920,1671]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 37. Habitus of Sagola species in the auripila species-group, dorsal views. a) S. auripila, b) S. spiniventris," figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907837/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[1053,1092,778,799]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="3.7" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="g" value="37.0">37g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
). Meso-and metathorax trapezoidal, as long as wide. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[685,801,832,853]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Aedeagus:</emphasis>
Median lobe slender and simple (
<figureCitation box="[693,791,858,879]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[175,207,1229,1248]" captionTargetBox="[156,1165,188,1205]" captionTargetId="figure-182@65.[151,1171,183,1212]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 38. Sagola species in the auripila species-group. Aedeagi, dorsal views: a) S. auripila, b) S. spiniventris, c) S. chathamensis, d) S. pittensis, e) S. chandleri, f) S. threekingsensis, g) S. gimmeli, h) S. sokolovi, lateral view, i) S. sokolovi. Dorsal surface of male head: j) S. spiniventris (arrow indicates wide frontal sulcus), k) S. chathamensis (arrow indicates narrow frontal sulcus). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907839" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907839/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[749,791,858,879]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="3.8" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="g" value="38.0">38g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
). Phallobase of median lobe symmetrical and rounded (
<figureCitation box="[928,1045,884,906]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[175,207,1229,1248]" captionTargetBox="[156,1165,188,1205]" captionTargetId="figure-182@65.[151,1171,183,1212]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 38. Sagola species in the auripila species-group. Aedeagi, dorsal views: a) S. auripila, b) S. spiniventris, c) S. chathamensis, d) S. pittensis, e) S. chandleri, f) S. threekingsensis, g) S. gimmeli, h) S. sokolovi, lateral view, i) S. sokolovi. Dorsal surface of male head: j) S. spiniventris (arrow indicates wide frontal sulcus), k) S. chathamensis (arrow indicates narrow frontal sulcus). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907839" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907839/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[980,1017,885,906]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="3.8" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="g" value="38.0">38g</quantity>
–h
</figureCitation>
). Parameres asymmetrical, left long, bent with divided apex (
<figureCitation box="[692,804,937,959]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[175,207,1229,1248]" captionTargetBox="[156,1165,188,1205]" captionTargetId="figure-182@65.[151,1171,183,1212]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 38. Sagola species in the auripila species-group. Aedeagi, dorsal views: a) S. auripila, b) S. spiniventris, c) S. chathamensis, d) S. pittensis, e) S. chandleri, f) S. threekingsensis, g) S. gimmeli, h) S. sokolovi, lateral view, i) S. sokolovi. Dorsal surface of male head: j) S. spiniventris (arrow indicates wide frontal sulcus), k) S. chathamensis (arrow indicates narrow frontal sulcus). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907839" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907839/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[742,778,938,959]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="3.8" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="g" value="38.0">38g</quantity>
–h
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="70" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="69.[685,1173,194,1065]" box="[709,1098,964,985]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,840,964,985]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingRegion box="[853,949,964,985]" country="New Zealand" name="Northland" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Northland</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[964,1038,964,985]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="68.[197,229,1638,1657]" captionTargetBox="[177,654,1079,1613]" captionTargetId="figure-619@68.[173,659,1076,1615]" captionTargetPageId="68" captionText="Fig. 40. Known collection localities of New Zealand Sagola species. S. pittensis: black circle; S. chandleri: triangles; S. threekingsensis: black square; S. gimmeli: star; S. sokolovi: white circles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907843" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907843/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
: star).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="69.[685,1173,194,1065]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,794,991,1012]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Habitat.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[853,936,991,1012]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">holotype</typeStatus>
of this species was collected by pyrethrin-fogging fungusy logs in hardwood and podocarp forests.
</paragraph>
